{{Infobox Website | name = Don Markstein's Toonopedia | logo = Dmarkstein.jpg | caption = Toonopedia Logo | url = [http://toonopedia.com/ toonopedia.com] | commercial = No | type = [[Internet encyclopedia]] | language = American English | registration = No | owner = Don Markstein | author = Don Markstein | launch date = {{Start date and age|2001|2|13}} | current status = | content license = [[All rights reserved]] }}
'''Don Markstein's Toonopedia''' (subtitled '''A Vast Repository of Toonological Knowledge''') is a [[World Wide Web|web]] [[encyclopedia]] of print [[cartoon]]s, [[comic strip]]s and animation, initiated February 13, 2001. '''Donald D. Markstein''', the sole writer and editor of Toonopedia, termed it "the world's first hypertext encyclopedia of toons" and stated, "The basic idea is to cover the entire spectrum of American cartoonery."
Markstein began the project during 1999 with several earlier titles: he changed '''Don's Cartoon Encyberpedia''' (1999) to '''Don Markstein's Cartoonopedia''' (2000) after learning the word "Encyberpedia" had been trademarked. During 2001, he settled on his final title, noting, "Decided (after thinking about it for several weeks) to change the name of the site to Don Markstein's Toonopedia, rather than Cartoonopedia. Better rhythm in the name, plus 'toon' is probably a more apt word, in modern parlance, than "cartoon", for what I'm doing.<ref name=bio>[http://www.toonopedia.com/don.htm About the Author: Don Markstein] at Don Markstein's Toonopedia. [https://www.webcitation.org/62hhV9j0g?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/don.htm Archived] October 25, 2011.</ref>
==Comic strips== Toonopedia author Donald David Markstein<ref name=spurgeon-obit>{{cite web| url = http://www.comicsreporter.com/index.php/don_markstein_1947_2012 | date= March 12, 2012|title=Don Markstein, 1947–2012| authorlink= Tom Spurgeon | first=Tom|last= Spurgeon| publisher=ComicsReporter.com| archivedate= March 15, 2012|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120315214313/http://www.comicsreporter.com/index.php/don_markstein_1947_2012}}</ref> (March 21, 1947&nbsp;– March 11, 2012)<ref name=spurgeon-obit /><ref name=sfsite>{{cite web| url= https://www.sfsite.com/news/tag/don-markstein/| first=Rodger, ed.|last= Turner| title=Obituary: Don Markstein| publisher= SFSite.com|date = March 12, 2012|accessdate= September 16, 2016|archivedate=May 11, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120511205149/http://www.sfsite.com/news/tag/don-markstein/| deadurl=no}}</ref> was fascinated with all forms of cartoon art since his childhood. During 1981, Markstein and his wife, GiGi Dane (August 7, 1949&nbsp;- August 5, 2016), founded ''Apatoons'', an [[amateur press association]] devoted to animation. He edited ''[[Comics Revue]]'', a monthly anthology of newspaper comics, from 1984 to 1987, and 1992 to 1996.<ref name=bio /> A writer for [[Disney comics|Walt Disney Comics]], Markstein based Toonopedia on American and other [[English language]] cartoons with the goal of developing the largest online resource concerning American cartoons. Toonopedia accumulated over 1,800 articles since its launch on February 13, 2001.
During 2002, Charles Bowen reviewing the site for ''[[Editor & Publisher]]'', said, {{quote|For journalists researching stories, these online resources can be golden. A case in point is Don Markstein's simply amazing Toonopedia, a vast repository of information about comics, past and future. Now, honestly, unless you're a comic book collector or a cartoonist, you're probably not going to put this on your frequent filer's list. However, if you're working on a story that deals with pop culture, that focuses on a particular time period, or that touches on classic villains and superheroes, Don just might become your own personal hero. The site serves up illustrated entries on nearly every comic strip, cartoon, and comic book you can think of, from the world famous ''[[Blondie (comic strip)|Blondie]]'' and ''[[Peanuts]]'' to those ultra-obscure strips, such as ''The Pie-Face Prince of Old Pretzelburg''.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.editorandpublisher.com/Article/Toonopedia-Is-Simply-Amazing-Comic-Resource |last=Bowen|first= Charles|title=Toonopedia Is Simply Amazing Comic Resource|work=[[Editor & Publisher]]| date=July 9, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025000000/http://www.editorandpublisher.com/Article/Toonopedia-Is-Simply-Amazing-Comic-Resource|archivedate=October 25, 2011|deadurl=no|accessdate=October 25, 2011}}</ref>}}
Markstein worked on the staff of the ''[[New Orleans Times-Picayune]]'' newspaper, writing feature stories for the [[Sunday magazine]] section.{{cn|date=September 2016}} His freelance credits include weekly restaurant reviews for the ''[[American City Business Journals|Phoenix Business Journal]]'',{{cn|date=September 2016}} semi-annual previews of comic book publishing projects, science fiction convention program books, scripts for relaxation tapes and computer manuals.{{cn|date=September 2016}} His comic book scripts are mainly for licensed characters, including [[Donald Duck]], [[Mickey Mouse]], [[Mighty Morphin Power Rangers]], and [[Eek! the Cat]].<ref name=bio />
''Graphic Novel Review for Libraries'' was Markstein's periodical guide for librarians. For each 20-page issue of the monthly magazine, he reviewed 25–30 graphic novels.{{cn|date=September 2016}}
He provided editing, design and production for numerous publications, including ''Arizona Living'', ''Arizona Women's Voice'', ''Comics Interview'', ''Comics Revue'', ''Phoenix'', ''Phoenix Resource'', ''Louisiana Weekly Employer'', ''Scottsdale'' and ''Sun Tennis''.{{cn|date=September 2016}}
In February 2011, Markstein, who had a history of strokes, suffered what his daughter called "an incident that caused him to be in and out of hospitals for several weeks", and the following month "suffered a massive stroke while in the hospital. This caused him to be paralyzed on his left side."<ref name=comicscube>Markstein's daughter, Rachel Brown, in {{cite web|title=Write Your Own Toonopedia Article|url=http://www.comicscube.com/2012/01/write-your-own-toonopedia-article.html| first=Duy. ed.|last= Tano|publisher=ComicsCube.com| accessdate=January 27, 2012| archivedate=April 24, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120424140510/http://www.comicscube.com/2012/01/write-your-own-toonopedia-article.html| deadurl=no}}</ref> He died of respiratory failure in March 2012.<ref name="NewsFromME">{{cite web |url=http://www.newsfromme.com/2012/03/11/don-markstein-r-i-p/ |title=Don Markstein, R.I.P. |publisher=News from Me |authorlink=Mark Evanier |last=Evanier |first=Mark |date=March 11, 2012 |accessdate=2012-03-11 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/665q7FpFp?url=http://www.newsfromme.com/2012/03/11/don-markstein-r-i-p/ |archivedate=March 11, 2012 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> In 2012, Markstein's family announced plans to continue updating Toonopedia through new articles written by fans,<ref name=comicscube /> but the site has yet to be updated since February 2011.
==Books== [[File:Princevaliantcompanion.jpg|thumb|''A Prince Valiant Companion'', co-edited by Markstein]] The subject matter of Toonopedia overlaps with the books Markstein wrote, edited and compiled. ''A Prince Valiant Companion'' (Manuscript Press, 1992), by Todd Goldberg and Carl J. Horak, was edited by Markstein and [[Rick Norwood]]. It includes plot summaries of the ''[[Prince Valiant]]'' comic strip from its beginning in 1937 to the 1980 retirement of the strip's creator, [[Hal Foster]], along with additional material on the series and Foster's other work.
''Hot Tips from Top Comics Creators'' (Fictioneer Books, 1994) is a 120-page collection of more 1,000 pieces of advice on the comic-book industry from the first ten years of ''Comics Interview'', plus capsule biographies of 262 comics professionals.
''Pirates!: The CD-ROM'' (PiratePubs, 1998) is a digital compendium of stories, games, movie stills, poetry, artwork, flags and music about pirates.
